",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-02T14:27:39.119Z\",\"permissionMode\":\"acceptEdits\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"1c574d06-97ea-4354-be3b-ea26912b252a\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"f766655b-80c9-49b8-8734-8bf7b86bdd8d\",\"version\":\"2.1.62\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"polished-sprouting-rose\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01M5xDJ6iERVqXFFVjTdeRaG\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"thinking\",\"thinking\":\"The user is asking about whether the `LastInteractionTime` gets updated during a turn when the agent makes a git commit. Let me think about this...\\n\\nThe hooks that fire during a Claude Code session:\\n1. `UserPromptSubmit` (TurnStart) - fires when user sends a prompt → updates `LastInteractionTime`\\n2. `Stop` (TurnEnd) - fires when agent finishes turn → updates `LastInteractionTime`\\n3. `PreToolUse[Task]` / `PostToolUse[Task]` - fires for Task tool calls (subagents)\\n4. `prepare-commit-msg` / `post-commit` - git hooks, NOT agent hooks\\n\\n\\n5. Git hooks don't trigger agent lifecycle events, so a commit mid-turn won't update `LastInteractionTime` — it stays frozen from when the turn started until the agent finishes. is: in a long agent turn (say 45+ minutes), could `LastInteractionTime` be older than 1 hour? Yes, if the turn started more than 1 hour ago and no other interaction hooks have fired.\\n\\nBut wait - the user is asking a more specific question. They're asking: when the agent calls `git commit`, does that trigger any hook that would update `LastInteractionTime`? \\n\\nFor Claude Code: The agent calls the Bash tool to run `git commit`. This is NOT a Task tool call, so `PreToolUse[Task]` doesn't fire. The git hooks (`prepare-commit-msg`, `post-commit`) fire but those are git hooks that don't update `LastInteractionTime`.\\n\\nThe available hooks are `UserPromptSubmit` and `Stop` for updating `LastInteractionTime`, plus `PreToolUse[Task]` and `PostToolUse[Task]` for subagent tasks, but git hooks themselves don't trigger any of these. So during a long turn, if the agent runs `git commit` via Bash without any Task tool calls, `LastInteractionTime` stays frozen at the turn start. This means the 1-hour threshold could become stale well before we'd expect it to, especially if the agent is actively working but just not triggering the right hooks. the real issue is that LastInteractionTime only gets updated at TurnStart, so a single turn lasting 90 minutes would appear stale after just 1 hour, triggering unnecessary overlap checks and potentially skipping condensation. I could extend the threshold to something like 24 hours—a session abandoned that long is clearly inactive—or switch to a different signal like TurnID instead of relying on time alone. They're right that 1 hour could be too short for long-running turns where the agent is actively working but hasn't triggered a new interaction timestamp. Since we only update `LastInteractionTime` on turn starts (not on individual tool calls like Bash), a complex multi-step task could easily exceed that window. I should probably increase the threshold to something like 12 or 24 hours, or find a different signal entirely—maybe looking at `Phase`, `StepCount`, or the relationship between `BaseCommit` and the current HEAD instead.\\n\\nActually, checking if the process is still running would be too fragile, and monitoring the transcript file's modification time is filesystem-dependent. I think the best approach is a generous time threshold combined with the overlap check as a fallback. The real question isn't \\\"is the session alive?\\\" but \\\"should we trust `hasNew` and skip the overlap check?\\\" With a 24-hour window, active sessions in short turns would skip the overlap check and condense correctly, while stale sessions killed days ago would fall back to the overlap check and avoid condensing.\\n\\nFor a session that went stale 1