mes per turn. That creates real costs: latency on every tool call, constant disk I/O for session state updates, all just to bump a timestamp. Instead, I should look at a lightweight heartbeat mechanism that fires periodically rather than on every call, or just leverage the existing PostToolUse hooks we already have without adding new ones.\\n\\nActually, the most direct fix might be using the `prepare-commit-msg` git hook that's already running — I could update LastInteractionTime right there before the PostCommit check happens. Though that creates a new problem: stale sessions would no longer be stale if their timestamp keeps getting refreshed, unless I'm selective about when to update it based on whether there's actually new content to commit.\\n\\nLet me step back and think about what a general \\\"alive\\\" signal architecture would actually need. type**\\n- Add `EventAlive` to the session phase state machine\\n- Map it from existing per-tool hooks\\n- ACTIVE + Alive → ACTIVE (ActionUpdateLastInteraction)\\n- Light-weight: just updates the timestamp, no other actions\\n\\n**Option B: Use existing tool hooks more broadly**\\n- For Claude Code: add PostToolUse[Bash] hook → maps to Alive event\\n- For Gemini: already has `after-tool *` → could map to Alive event\\n- For OpenCode/Cursor: depends on their hook support\\n\\n**Option C: Periodic heartbeat**\\n- A background process that periodically signals \\\"I'm alive\\\"\\n- More complex, requires daemon/process management\\n\\nThe real question is whether we should hook into tool calls broadly or be selective. We already have tool-level hooks firing for some agents like Gemini, but for Claude Code we're only capturing Task and TodoWrite events. I could expand to Bash calls specifically to catch things like `git commit` without the noise of hooking every single tool invocation. But this is really about the bigger architectural picture — how do we want to signal agent liveness across different platforms?\",\"signature\":\"\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":4140,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":152187,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":4140},\"output_tokens\":10,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYeR3tRiWaPCpeBZ7wyx6\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"da59153a-52f5-44cf-a473-94ee17e709a2\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-02T14:32:03.004Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"da59153a-52f5-44cf-a473-94ee17e709a2\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"f766655b-80c9-49b8-8734-8bf7b86bdd8d\",\"version\":\"2.1.62\",\"gitBranch\":\"main\",\"slug\":\"polished-sprouting-rose\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01ESygqbU4Un1XyCjB3HogsP\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Great question. Let me lay out what I found and what the options are.\\n\\nThe current hook landscape per agent:\\n\\n| Hook point | Claude Code | Gemini CLI | OpenCode | Cursor | Factory AI |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| Session start/end | yes | yes | yes | yes | yes |\\n| Turn start/end | yes | yes | yes | yes | yes |\\n| **Per-tool (every call)** | no (Task+TodoWrite only) | **yes** (`before-tool *`, `after-tool *`) | no | no | no (Task only) |\\n| Compaction | no | yes | yes | yes | yes |\\n\\nGemini already fires hooks on **every** tool call. For Claude Code, we only hook `Task` and `TodoWrite` — so `Bash` (which runs `git commit`), `Write`, `Edit`, `Read` etc. are all invisible.\\n\\nThere are a few approaches to an \\\"alive\\\" signal:\\n\\n**Option A: Add a dedicated `Alive` event to the state machine.** Map it from broader tool hooks. `ACTIVE + Alive → ACTIVE (ActionUpdateLastInteraction)` — a lightweight transition that only touches the timestamp. Then we configure it on whichever tool hooks each agent supports.\\n\\n**Option B: Hook `Bash` specifically for Claude Code.** This is the narrowest change that catches `git commit`. Add `PostToolUse[Bash]` → maps to Alive event. But it still misses Write/Edit tool calls that don't go through Bash.\\n\\n**Option C: Hook all tool calls (wildcard matcher).** Claude Code supports `PostToolUse` with matchers — we could add a `\\\"*\\\"` matcher (like Gemini already has). But this fires on every single tool call (hundreds per turn), adding latency to each one.\\n\\nThe performance concern with C is real — each hook invocation is a subprocess `entire hooks claude-code post-tool-use`, which means exec + JSON parse + state file read/write. At hundreds of calls per turn, that's meaningful.\\n\\nA middle ground: **Option A with selective hooks**. Add the `Alive` event type, but only wire it to hooks that aren't too chatty — like `Bash` for Claude Code (maybe 5-20 calls per turn), and `after-tool *` for Gemini (which already fires on everything). That gives us a much fresher `LastInteractionTime` without the overhead of hooking every Read/Glob/Grep.\\n\\nWant me to plan out the `Alive` event approach? The scope would be:\\n1. Add `EventAlive` to the session phase state machine (trivial transition: update timestamp, stay in same phase)\\n2. Add a new normalized hook type (or reuse an existing one)\\n3. Wire it up for Claude Code via `PostToolUse[Bash]` (and potentially `PostToolUse[Write]`)\\n4. For Gemini, map from the existing `after-tool *` hook\\n\\nThat would let us drop the 24-hour threshold in `shouldCondenseWithOverlapCheck` down to something much tighter, or even remove the time check entirely and use a \\\"has the session had any alive signal since the last TurnStart?\\\" boolean.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":4140,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":152187,\"output_tokens\":1822,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0}