-373) tests the **exact same scenario** through the actual hook binary, which is strictly more realistic.\\n\\nHaving both is defensible (unit tests run faster, integration tests catch wiring bugs), but the unit test is doing so much manual setup that it is basically a worse integration test. If you want to keep both, the unit test could be significantly tightened.\\n\\nSpecific redundancies in the unit test:\\n- Lines 2181-2188: Writing a `.gitstats_cache.sqlite3` file and creating metadata dir. This is boilerplate that `setupSessionWithCheckpoint` already does for other tests, but this test does it manually.\\n- Lines 2190-2196: Writing a transcript file inline -- same pattern as 5 other tests in this file.\\n- Lines 2220-2221: `now := time.Now()` / `state.LastInteractionTime = &now` -- could be a one-liner with a helper or at least `timePtr(time.Now())`.\\n\\n**4. E2E test exists for a low-level logic change**\\n\\n`/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/e2e/tests/mid_turn_commit_test.go`\\n\\nThis is 56 lines that make real API calls to agents. The CLAUDE.md explicitly warns: \\\"IMPORTANT: Do NOT run E2E tests proactively. E2E tests make real API calls to agents, which consume tokens and cost money.\\\"\\n\\nThe bug is in `shouldCondenseWithOverlapCheck` -- a pure logic function that takes `(bool, *time.Time)` and returns `bool`. The unit test + integration test already fully cover the regression. The E2E test adds a real agent calling Claude to create markdown files about fruits. That is a significant cost for marginal confidence gain over the integration test, which already exercises the full hook binary.\\n\\nThis is a YAGNI violation: the E2E test is \\\"just in case\\\" the integration test misses something, but the integration test already runs the real binary with real git operations.\\n\\n**5. Passing `*time.Time` through the call chain instead of a bool**\\n\\n`/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 602, 6